Process model


We consider the following model: \begin{equation*} \dfrac{\textrm{d}T(t)}{\textrm{d}t}=-k\left(T(t) - T_a\right), \end{equation*}

which has solution \begin{equation*} T(t)=\left(T(0)-T_{a}\right)\textrm{e}^{-kt}+T_{a}. \end{equation*}


Again, we assume that $T(0)$ is known (e.g. measurable) so that we infer two parameters

\begin{equation*} \theta=(T_{a},k)^\mathsf{T}. \end{equation*}

Noise (measurement) model


We use an additive Gaussian measurement model

\begin{equation*} T^{o}(t) \mid \theta = \mathcal{N}\left(T(t;\theta), \sigma^2\right). \end{equation*}


Series of $I$ measurements leads to log-likelihood function

\begin{equation*} \ell(\theta \mid T^{o}(t)) = \sum_{i=1}^{I} \log \left[\phi\left(T^{o}(t_i); T(t_i;\theta), \sigma^2 \right)\right], \end{equation*}

where $\phi(x; \mu, \sigma^2)$ denotes the probability density function of the normal distribution with mean $\mu$, variance $\sigma^2$.

Compute the posterior distribution


Start from Bayes' rule to write the posterior distribution as

\begin{equation*} \mathbb{P}(\theta\,|\,T^{o}(t))\propto\mathcal{L}(T^{o}(t)\,|\,\theta)\mathbb{P}(\theta), \end{equation*}

where $\mathcal{L}(T^{o}(t)\,|\,\theta)$ is the likelihood of the data and $\mathbb{P}(\theta)$ the prior distribution.


Recall that \begin{equation*} T^{o}(t_i)\sim\mathcal{N}\left(T(t_i),\sigma^2\right), \end{equation*}

so that the posterior can be written

\begin{equation*} \mathbb{P}(\theta\,|\,T^{o}(t))\propto\prod_{i=1}^{I}\phi\left(T^{o}(t_i);T(t_i),\sigma^2\right)\mathbb{P}(\theta). \end{equation*}

Markov chain Monte Carlo sampler


Iteratively generate a sequence of samples from the posterior distribution $\theta_i$, for $i=1,2,\ldots$

  1. Given $\theta_i$, generate $\tilde\theta$ as \begin{equation*} \tilde\theta=q(\tilde\theta\,|\,\cdot). \end{equation*}
  2. Accept the move, and set $\theta_{i+1}=\tilde\theta$, with probability \begin{equation*} r=\text{min}\left(1,\frac{\mathbb{P}(\tilde\theta\,|\,T^{o}(t))}{\mathbb{P}(\theta_i\,|\,T^{o}(t))}\right). \end{equation*}

Here we start with $\theta_0=\theta_\text{MLE}$, using a multivariate Normal for the proposal kernel, $q$, and discard the first $N_\text{burn-in}$ iterations.

Chain convergence - Gelman's convergence statistic

Run $J$ chains of $L$ samples each (after discarding the burn-in) and compute:

  • $\bar\theta^j$ - Mean value of chain $j$;
  • $\bar\theta^*$ - Mean of the mean of all chains;
  • $B=\frac{L}{J-1}\sum_{j=1}^J\left(\bar\theta^j-\bar\theta^*\right)^2$ - Variance of the means of the chains;
  • $W=\frac{1}{J}\sum_{j=1}^J\left(\frac{1}{L-1}\sum_{l=1}^L\left(\theta_i^{(j)}-\bar\theta^j\right)^2\right)$ - averaged variances of the individual chains across all chains.

Then we consider the chains as having converged when \begin{equation*} R=\frac{\frac{L-1}{L}W+\frac{1}{L}B}{W}<1.01. \end{equation*}
